2","1243–1292":"1243–1292","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1272":"1240–1272","1243–1292":"1243–1292","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Beaumont was born in 1240, in France, his father, William Beaumont, was 25 and his mother, Jeanne D'Acquigny, was 30. He married Isabeau de Marly de Montmorency in 1265. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1269, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1272":"1240–1272","1243–1292":"1243–1292","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1272":"1240–1272","1243–1292":"1243–1292","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1272":"1240–1272","1243–1292":"1243–1292","1215–1280":"1215–1280","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Beaumont-en-Gâtinais, Sein